entry.author: jeremybentham
entry.content: A very long time ago in a different part of the world lived a poor boy and his widow mother, and their only possession was a cow. They lived off of the milk that the cow gave them, until hard times came and this was no longer enough. The mother told the boy to take the cow to market and sell it, and the boy set out with the cow intending to do so. However, he was persuaded by a stranger along the road to sell his cow for five beans. The stranger said they were magic, and the boy could see that they did not resemble ordinary beans. They were large and smooth and round, almost spherical, and very hard, with a thin line that ran all the way around the widest part. They were a dark green color, almost black. They were identical to the stone that rested inside Esther's pocket.

entry.author: Phil Khaisman
entry.content: Later that night... Esther walked through the night to the Meeting. The stone was still there, in her pocket, and she took it out once more to examine it as closely as she could. She stopped underneath a streetlight, the cone of light illuminating the stone. It sure looked like an ordinary stone, but it didn't feel it. Something stirred within her, unbeknownst to her except for a rumble in her stomach and an exceptionally loud belch. A nearby feline darted for cover at the unexpected sound. Esther herself jumper for she had never belched so loud. No, her diet of legumes and the occasional petunia could not concoct such a barbarous and carnivorous explosion of sound. She promptly dropped the stone on the ground. It fell without a bounce as Esther ran to the meeting, wanting nothing to do with it and its mysterious ability to induce such a sound, for this is no doubt what she suspected. She entered the meeting, attempting to hide her feelings of worry. She sat down in the chair, but as she did so, she felt something in her pocket. She reached down, curious, and touched...the stone. BAAARRAAGAAA!!! She belched! This time louder! And more vicious\! And oh the horror of it all! A bird from the rafters of the building fell to the floor, dead...

entry.author: Gabe Lorenz
entry.content: At the sound, and indeed smell, of such a ghastly belch, the other women at the meeting all jumped a solid 2 feet in the air. Quite an impressive feat for a bunch of flower picking ninny-muggins if I do say so myself. After many a muttered disgusted comment and disapproving glance, the ladies finally settled back into their seats only to have Esther topple onto the floor, writhing and convulsing as if possessed. Now, as you can imagine, since a simple belch got their panties all in a tizzy, the other group members lost the proverbial "it" and all fled towards the nearest exit leaving Esther to live or die as the universe saw fit

entry.author: Phil Khaisman
entry.content: Now the universe is a very funny thing for the universe indeed saw fit a course of action, but this course of action was not her death, no, the universe had something much grander in mind. As Esther awoke from her spasm of shame, she looked over and saw what else but the stone. Without thinking, she reached out and held it tight and true for it was...precious. In her convulsing she had, as she put it years later, a feeling of all that was to come. But again, it was just a feeling. She stood up feeling strong...and hungry. She felt a hunger such as she has never felt before. No amount of petunias could satiate her hunger. Ha! Petunias! The word itself made her cackle. Had the others been around their panties would have not only been in a tizzy, but in a rancor, akin to the hissing of a venomous viper of vehement and voracious doom. A volcano erupted nearby; no doubt an effect of her cackle. But she took no notice. She began to deftly walk towards the door. It was closed. It made no difference for she walked right through, leaving bricks and dust and an outline of her no-longer feeble frame. At this point she knew what she would, and she had the stone clutched in her hand. There is no doubt what she would do…

entry.author: Gabe Lorenz
entry.content: She convulsed once more, but this time voluntarily, and upon a twitch of her shoulders she sprouted wings, a shake of her heard a snout, and a roll of her body and shiny sleek and solid scales covered her entire frame. The last tremor of her body dropped her onto all fours and she assumed the form of a terrifying yet beautiful dragon. Sensing her new found might she lept into the air and flew east. Not knowing exactly where she was going or even why she was going to this mystical place, that seemed to be drawing her in with an exponentially greater force of attraction than the gravitational pull of something as robust as the planet of JUPITER, she beat her wings harder and faster until the thunderous tumult the wind she was creating with each flap was devastating the homes beneath her. She made but one stop before reaching her destination and that was at her house where she unleashed a torrent of flame that incinerated her once beloved petunias...

entry.author: PK
entry.content: In the near past Esther was in fact growing her pittiful petunias in The Shire of Middle Earth and her mystical urge as a dragon led her to a more otherworldy location. For this location she chose the earth, our earth. As she entered, through the Atlantic Mid Ocean Ridge which was in fact a maelstrom of untold power and also a portal as it were, she looked upon naught but the blue ocean. The once woman named Esther, who was now in fact a dragon - i mention this if the previous passage was not enough to instill her transformation, weakly written as it were - got incredibly depressed and became an incredibly racist dragon. This was a horrid transformation for as racist as people are and the horrors they induce, imagine the horrors that a racist dragon could inflict upon the world!

entry.author: jeremybentham
entry.content:
Fortunately for the world, she soon had an encounter with a badly burnt Albanian boy which completely cured her of racism forever. This story is recorded elsewhere, so I'll not repeat it here. Suffice it to say that Esther was once more filled with a love for humanity, and her greatest passion was her desire to rejoin the human race. While in dragon form Esther learned a lot about dragons. She learned that most dragons are both solitary and territorial, and will attack another dragon if it comes too close. She and learned that while dragons are primarily aerial creatures, they are also first cousins with sea monsters. As such, they can understand both bird- and fish-speak. And finally, she learned that dragons can cover quite a lot of ground when they wish to. She traveled many leagues, following rumors of magic lamp owners or potion recipes or any hint of a cure for her condition that the local wildlife could give her. But birds and fish have little brains, and thus cannot hold more than small pieces of information. They are often mistaken and very nearly always useless. So Esther was beginning to despair of ever finding her humanity again when the raven appeared with a new lead: A powerful sorcerer had learned of her story and was now looking for her.
"What does he want?" asked Esther. But that was all the raven could tell her.

entry.author: jeremybentham
entry.content: She met the sorcerer on a Saturday. Esther tried very hard to keep track of the date, just as she tried very hard to remember all the things she used to like back when she was human. She was afraid that she was slowly turning into a dragon on the inside, and that one day Esther the human would be no more. It was a very nice Saturday too, with the sun shining and only a couple clouds in the sky. Esther was just dining on a couple of sheep in an unattended pasture. It was quite picturesque, if you didn't mind the bits and pieces of leftover sheep. (I used to be such a tidy eater, Esther thought. But now it's all finger food.)

entry.author: jeremybentham
entry.content:
"Hi," he said. "My name's John J. J. Schmidt. I've been looking for you."
She turned around to face him, as calmly as she could. "I know."

The man did not look like a sorcerer. He didn't look like anything in particular other than a reasonably well-dressed gentleman.
"I can help you," he said. "You want to be human again, right?"
"How?"
"But I want something in return," he continued. "You found something, that day you changed you. Something small, and hard, and round. I want it."
"I don't have it," Esther replied. "It was in my pocket, and my pockets are gone."
"Your pockets and their contents will return with your human shape. All I want is your promise that you will give it it to me when the time comes."
"Very well. But I want to know who you are and why you want it. I want to know why," she carried on with just a hint of desperation, "why all this is happening to me."
"Agreed. What say you fly us back to your former abode where we can work the counter transformation, and on the way I shall tell you my story."
"Can't wizards fly?" she asked, only half sarcastically.
"I am not a wizard," he said as he climbed onto her back. "I am a horticulturist."

entry.author: jeremybentham
entry.content:
He settled himself, and she took off, spreading her great wings and beating the air powerfully.
"A horticulturist," he repeated. "In fact, one of the founding members of the society which you attend regularly. Or should I say, attended regularly. In any case, I'm sure you never guessed that your precious Horticulture Society was only a public chapter of a very old and very secret organization. What I am about to tell you, you must never reveal to another living soul. The name I gave you earlier--John Schmidt-- is not my true name. It is the name that all of us on the Council use whenever we go out. My real name...is Jack. And I know I look to be in my 30s, but I am really quite old. However, when I was a boy, I came across five magic seeds. I planted them together, and from those seeds grew a most singular plant. It was tremendous...it was beautiful...it was terrifying. I was very afraid. I destroyed it. But in death it yielded a crop of five more seeds. Because I was so afraid, I scattered those seeds throughout the world. But in time I regretted my decision, and so started the Horticulture Society to watch, and wait for when those seeds might reappear. We have found four of them already. The last one was found in--hmm!"
She landed with a thump. They had arrived at the remains of Esther's home.

entry.author: jeremybentham
entry.content: Esther had avoided this place ever since she became a dragon. This had been the little piece of the world that human Esther had claimed for herself, and dragon Esther did not think she would be able to bear the reminder. But as she looked at the blackened crater which had once housed her home and little garden, she felt nothing. Just emptiness, like a sort of mental hole where her emotions ought to be.

entry.author: jeremybentham
entry.content:
The horticulturist, whatever his name was, knelt in the scorched dirt. He scratched around in the soil for a bit before scooping something out. Esther watched him anxiously.
"Will you turn into a dragon once I give you the stone?" she asked him.
"Don't be silly," he replied. "It wasn't the seed which turned you into a dragon in the first place. It was this!" and he held forth a petunia bulb.
"The flower turned you, and the root will turn you back. Eat it!"
Esther was very confused but she took the petunia bulb and swallowed it. And her wings slid off, followed by her claws, her scales, and the rest of her dragonish attributes. Just like a heavy set of clothes, she thought to herself. And then, just like that, she was human again.

entry.author: jeremybentham
entry.content: "We needed dragon ash for the soil," the horticulturist carried on in a conversational tone while she was changing, "and dragons are so rare these days. I arranged for the flower to be brought here,with the knowledge that one of the members here loved petunias...of course we didn't realize that you would discover--ah! You are human again! The stone, please."

entry.author: Shikah
entry.content: I find this post very interesting and thoghut provoking different cultural definitions of what is love. As a Latina, I can relate to Esther's point of view. As a person who grew up in North America, I can understand, somewhat, the North American teacher's perspective. As I write this, I realize that on the spectrum of dependence vs independence as described by Esther, I fall closer to Esther than to the North American teacher. Can we learn from both and take the positives from each in order to blend them into something better? Possibly. I do believe children need to develop independence and I also believe they get there through the love and support of a more knowledgeable other , in this case the teacher. So, the child needs help knowing what to do and we teach the child, with our words and our actions, what he needs to do/know in order to become independent at hand washing, for example. Slowly, we relinquish more and more responsibility to the child using encouraging words and tips, as needed. I don't think always doing it for the child or leaving him/her alone is best. To me, they are both extremes on a continuum. The most important piece of this discussion needs to be what is our goal for this child? What is his/her goal? Once we've figured this out then we can determine appropriate teaching strategies.

entry.author: Catherine Grubb
entry.content: Esther and the horticulturist were taken aback. "What...what is it? What's happened?" Esther stammered, her mouth agape at the gleaming radiance before her. "Why, she's broken the fourth wall my dear," said the horticulturist. "Try not to look, it's a little unclear what could happen to a protagonist were she to see, well, something like this." "Pro- protagonist?" Esther was feeling faint. "Never you mind dear," the horticulturist said, in an uncharacteristically soothing tone.

entry.author: jeremybentham
entry.content:
"Please, Ms. Danberry," he continued, maneuvering himself in between her and the ...thing. "I truly regret the extent of your involvement. This will all be over shortly. It's just a tiny hole in the fabric of the universe. Nature abhors a vacuum my dear, but a world tree needs space to grow, and with the..."

He pattered on in that calm, relaxed tone, sounding for all the world like one of the ladies at the Horticulture Society Meeting discussing a new project. But Esther was having a hard time following him. She felt torn between her elation at finally being human again and a very dragonish urge to claw this man's eyes out. For quite a while Esther had felt a victim of people and forces beyond her understanding. And now it seemed like the answers were very close, perhaps wrapped up in that mysterious light behind the horticulturist...

"...not technically an ash tree, but a dragon-ash tree! But you can't make an Yggdrasil without breaking a few eggs, and in this case..."

He was still rambling, and slowly moving closer to her. But Esther couldn't pay attention. The whole world seemed to wobble when she looked toward the (what did he call it? something about a wall?). She struggled to hold on to any kind of concrete thought, and eventually one idea with substance crossed her mind.

I'm done.

She was done, she decided, with being the person to whom things happened. And she was especially done with being the person who got turned into a dragon so other people could run their silly science experiment, or whatever it was.

The horticulturist was very close now. "...necessary, but if you had just left the seed in place, things would have..."

And it was then that Esther did something which the pre-dragon Esther would have found inconceivable. She shoved him hard to the ground. And then the light was directly in front of her, and she couldn't help but look, and briefly make eye contact with YOU, the reader. This was too much for her already fragile state, and she managed to take three shaky steps before collapsing in a dead faint.

When she awoke, both the light and the horticulturist were gone. In their place was the biggest plant she had ever seen. It was wider around than her old house had been, and stretched off into unimaginable distances in the sky. The beanstalk, she thought with wonder. Then another thought came to her. She slipped a hand into her pocket. The stone was gone.

entry.author: jeremybentham
entry.content:
So. Old Whatshisname must have taken his stone, planted it, and then climbed his stupid beanstalk to who knows where. Well. It seemed she had a choice. She could attempt to forget this ever happened, and try to pick up the shattered pieces of her former life, probably moving somewhere far far away...or...she didn't even know why it occurred to her...she could climb the beanstalk.

It was crazy. It was crazy and she was crazy for thinking about it. Why was she thinking about it?
